Certainly! You can write a function in Java that checks if a given pattern occurs in a string using the `String` class's `contains` method or by using regular expressions. Below, I'll show you a simple implementation using both methods:

### Using `String.contains` Method

```java
public class PatternChecker {
    // Method to check if the pattern exists in the text
    public static boolean containsPattern(String text, String pattern) {
        // Using the contains method of the String class
        return text.contains(pattern);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String text = "This is a sample string.";
        String pattern = "sample";

        // Check if the pattern is present in the text
        boolean result = containsPattern(text, pattern);

        // Output the result
        if (result) {
            System.out.println("The pattern '" + pattern + "' is found in the text.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("The pattern '" + pattern + "' is not found in the text.");
        }
    }
}
```

### Using Regular Expressions

```java
import java.util.regex.Pattern;
import java.util.regex.Matcher;

public class PatternChecker {

    // Method to check if the pattern exists in the text using regex
    public static boolean containsPattern(String text, String pattern) {
        // Compile the pattern into a regex pattern
        Pattern compiledPattern = Pattern.compile(pattern);
        // Create a matcher to find the pattern in the text
        Matcher matcher = compiledPattern.matcher(text);
        // Return if the pattern exists in the text
        return matcher.find();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String text = "This is a sample string.";
        String pattern = "sample";

        // Check if the pattern is present in the text
        boolean result = containsPattern(text, pattern);

        // Output the result
        if (result) {
            System.out.println("The pattern '" + pattern + "' is found in the text.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("The pattern '" + pattern + "' is not found in the text.");
        }
    }
}
```

Both methods will effectively check if the given pattern occurs in the string. The first method is straightforward and works well for simple substring searches. The second method is more flexible and powerful, allowing for complex pattern matching using regular expressions. Choose the method that best suits your needs!
